ain\f1\fs20\cf0\ri140 marginal cost.\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr B) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\ri140 net loss.\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr C) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0 activity cost.\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr D) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\ri140 opportunity cost.\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr E) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\ri140 foregone cost.\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr 8) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\ri140 Making optimal decisions "at the margin" requires\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr A) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\ri140 making decisions according to one's whims and fancies. \par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr B) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\ri140 weighing the costs and benefits of a decision.\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr C) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0 advanced knowledge of economics.\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr D) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\ri140 making borderline decisions.\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr E) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\ri140 making consistently irrational decisions.\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr 9) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\ri140 As professors and teachers get closer to retirement age they typically spend more time reading and thinking about the financial planning as well as the stock market. By gathering and using all available information as they act to achieve their goals, these teachers are exemplifying the economic idea that\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr A) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\ri140 people respond to economic incentives.\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr B) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\ri140 equity is more important than efficiency.\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr C) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0 people make identical choices.\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr D) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\ri140 people are rational.\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr E) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\ri140 optimal decisions are made at the margin.\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\par\pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf0\qr 10) \pard \plain\f1\fs20\cf